  • A workspace that allows you to aggregate, describe, and share research
  • A tool to improve reproducibility of data intensive science, recording progress as you work
  • A set of living research projects enabling contribution to large-scale collaborative solutions
  • Freely available to anyone

Enabling researchers to contribute to large-scale collaborative science across locales

Why use Synapse?

  1. It's free!
  2. Share data and results
  3. Collaborate across a Team
  4. Keep track of data processing steps
  5. Get attribution for work performed

Synapse for U4C

Up for a Challenge requires reproducibility and sharing of results and encourages collaboration across disciplines.


These are the things that Synapse was designed to support.


Synapse for U4C

Creating a Submission

We assume (and will not cover today) that:

  1. You have registered for a free Synapse account
  2. You have registered for the Challenge
  3. You have (optionally) formed and registered a Team
  4. You are familiar with the rules for the Challenge
  5. You have access to dbGaP data

All information can be found at the Challenge website:

https://www.synapse.org/upforachallenge

Synapse for U4C

Creating a Submission

https://www.synapse.org/upforachallenge


  1. Create a new Synapse Project
  2. Find the Project Submission Template
  3. Get the Wiki text from the template and copy it to your own Project Wiki
  4. Create necessary Folders
  5. Edit your Project Wiki (and other Project content) with your own content


Detailed information about these steps is available in section
4.5 - How to Submit A Challenge Entry.

Synapse for U4C

Creating a Submission Live Demo

Details are available at 4.5 - How to Submit A Challenge Entry


  1. Make sure you are logged into Synapse (check upper left)
  2. Start at 4.5 - How to Submit A Challenge Entry
  3. Click Create Project Button and create a new project (this takes to a blank project)
  4. Favorite it (click star) to easily find it again!
  5. Optionally, Share it with your team (if you have one, will share w/ U4C test team)
  6. Find the Project Submission Template
  7. Copy the wiki text to your own Project level Wiki
  8. Create two folders - one for Abstract and one for Code
  9. Edit the Wiki on the Abstract folder to contain the text of your Abstract
  10. Edit the Project-level Wiki with the content of your Submission (many features in Synapse to make this proj sharable and reproducible, talk about those now)
  1. Everything created gets a unique ID (synXXXXX) - can refer to any Project, File, or Folder that way

Creating a Submission


Before we explore an Example Project Submission, I'll discuss features provided by Synapse to create a sharable, reusable, and reproducible Submission.

Synapse Features

Wikis

  • We use a simple text-based formatting system called Markdown
  • You will use this to edit your Project Wiki with the content of your Submission
Since the Synapse web site is probably most often used, we have flexible options for describing the data in a Project

Synapse features

File storage

  • Agnostic to storage solution (cloud, local server, remote server)
  • New! - your own Amazon S3 buckets

Synapse features

Storing data using the web interface

Synapse features

Linking to dbGaP data

For this Challenge, dbGaP data cannot be uploaded to Synapse.

However, a file can be linked instead of stored, and can still be used by many features of Synapse.

Synapse features

Certified user


In order to add content to Synapse, Take the Quiz to become a Certified User!

Synapse features

Annotations

  • Easily curate and search for specific files and folders
  • Completely user-driven
  • A querying system to search

Example File with annotations


Synapse features

Provenance

Provenance = keeping track of inputs, outputs, and the code to run

  • Who did what to a file and when?
  • Retrieve in a computer-friendly manner
  • Do it while you work or later in the browser

Synapse features

Visualizing provenance in the browser

Synapse features

Synapse API

All features in the web browser are available from
R, Python, and the Command line for use in an
automated, reproducible manner.

Nearly all features of available in the web browser are available in the R and Python clients! * Project, File, Folder creation * Storing and linking files * Manipulating annotations * Manipulating provenance * Creating and updating tables * Making Wikis

Synapse for U4C

Submitting a Challenge Entry Live Demo

  1. Go to 4.5 - How to Submit A Challenge Entry, "How to Submit"
  2. Click Submit to Challenge button
  3. Find your Project
  4. Choose the U4C challenge
  5. Provide a name (same as your Project title)
  6. Choose submitting as indiv or team (I'll choose team)
  7. Submit!
  8. Check that your submission appears in the submissions list
  9. Share your project with the NCI U4C Evaluation Panel - they require view permissions
  10. Potentially share your project with the public, whenever you want!

Synapse features

Structured data tables

  • Data that is queryable, but also enforces the data type is stored in each column
  • Can share a link to the results of a specific query.
  • Can use results in Wiki, from programmatic clients

Example query:

SELECT UID,biologicalSampleName,Diffname_short,pass_qc,Cell_Type 
FROM syn3156503
WHERE public=true
We may want to have data that is queryable, but also enforce what data is entered - certain strings, a column of integers, etc A relatively new feature in Synapse

Synapse features

Annotations

  • User-structured metadata directly on files/folders
  • No types enforced like columns in table
q <- "select * from file where projectId=='syn2346643' and dataSubType=='cna'"
res <- synapseQuery(q)
name id dataType platform disease
JWGray_BCCL_SNP6_segmented_pnas.cbs.txt syn2346649 DNA Genome_Wide_SNP_6 cancer
JWGray_BCCL_SNP6_segmented_v2.cbs syn2347005 DNA Genome_Wide_SNP_6 cancer
JWGray_BCCL_SNP6_segmented_v2_gene_level.txt.zip syn2347007 DNA Genome_Wide_SNP_6 cancer

JWGray_BCCL_SNP6_segmented_v2_table.txt.zip syn2347009 DNA Genome_Wide_SNP_6 cancer

Wikis from RMarkdown

Sage-Bionetworks/knit2synapse

  • Run RMarkdown code directly to a Wiki (includes images, code, text)
  • An Example
library(knit2synapse)
knitfile2synapse("./foobaz.Rmd", owner="syn4157539", overwrite=TRUE)
  • Can do similar thing with IPython notebooks
